messages.text:
So I'm a noob too, So I could be wrong! 

BUT 

I believe that the terminal, yarn start/ yarn chain starts deploys the app and a blockchain to your local computer.  That is why you use the Rinkey Test Net to use a test network in 'the wild' that isn't hosted on your computer.  So once you use a yarn surge (to deploy your app to the rinkey test network) you are deploying it to somewhere on the internet. 

So once you get to checkpoint 6. you are no longer working with a applcation/chain that is local to your computer. (so the terminals are no longer needed for the rest of the challenge)

So I can toggle the location of eg node16 into my

text_entities.text: I have a set of lines like this in my .zshrc (on Mac):
alias node16='export PATH="/usr/local/bin:/opt/homebrew/opt/node@16/bin:$PATH"; echo -n "node "; node -v'
So I can toggle the location of eg node16 into my
$PATH

. BUT, on reflection, I did this outside of the "screen" my frontend was running in, so it would have had no affect. Conclusion: For me, mine was resolved just by restarting the frontend (Ctrl-C then "yarn start").

Looks like your deployer account doesn't have enough sepolia to deploy the contract.  yarn generate will create your deployer account, but you then need to fund it by sending it some sepolia.  Through your metamask or other wallet where you have some sepolia

yarn chain runs your local hardhat node, as at this point you shouldn't need it running.  yarn start runs your front end, so you will need that up until you create a surge page later.

or
devDependencies
. You can install it using Yarn with the following command:

package.json

.

package.json
and
yarn.lock

files are up to date and correctly reflect your project's dependencies.

text:
The error message "Recv failure: Connection was reset" often indicates a network issue during the Git clone operation. Here are a few steps you can take to troubleshoot and resolve the problem:

1.

- Ensure that your internet connection is stable. Try accessing other websites or resources to confirm.

2.

- Check if your firewall or antivirus software is blocking the Git connection. Temporarily disable them and try cloning the repository again.

3.
- If you have set up SSH keys, consider using the SSH URL for cloning instead of HTTPS. Change the clone command to:

- Sometimes, network issues can be transient. Retry the clone command after a short period.

5.
- If you are on Windows, consider using a Git credential manager. GitHub recommends using the Git Credential Manager for Windows. You can download and install it from [here](
- Check your Git configuration settings. Ensure that your username and email are correctly set.

text.text:
git config --global user.name "Your Name"
     git config --global user.email "your.email@example.com"

text:
- If you are using HTTPS, make sure you have the correct credentials (username and password or a personal access token). If you are using SSH, make sure your SSH key is correctly configured.

After trying these steps, you should be able to clone the repository successfully. If the issue persists, it might be worth checking with your network administrator or GitHub support for further assistance.

The error message "Recv failure: Connection was reset" often indicates a network issue during the Git clone operation. Here are a few steps you can take to troubleshoot and resolve the problem:

1.
Check Internet Connection:

- Ensure that your internet connection is stable. Try accessing other websites or resources to confirm.

2.
Firewall or Antivirus Blocking:

- Check if your firewall or antivirus software is blocking the Git connection. Temporarily disable them and try cloning the repository again.

3.
Use SSH Instead of HTTPS:
- If you have set up SSH keys, consider using the SSH URL for cloning instead of HTTPS. Change the clone command to:
git clone git@github.com:scaffold-eth/se-2-challenges.git challenge-0-simple-nft
Retry the Clone:

https://github.com/microsoft/Git-Credential-Manager-for-Windows
Git Config Settings:
- Check your Git configuration settings. Ensure that your username and email are correctly set.

git config --global user.name "Your Name"
     git config --global user.email "your.email@example.com"
HTTPS vs. SSH Authentication:

- If you are using HTTPS, make sure you have the correct credentials (username and password or a personal access token). If you are using SSH, make sure your SSH key is correctly configured.

After trying these steps, you should be able to clone the repository successfully. If the issue persists, it might be worth checking with your network administrator or GitHub support for further assistance.

I used to, no joke, run into a yarn problem and just reinstall my OS. I was well past the "fuck it" stage. 

I mean, I'd purge and reinstall and all that, and I have NO idea what was going on then that made me reinstall my OS. I did it a few times though.

I'm determined to not be drama this time through the bleach.

This is a horse-training term, but I'm done "sneaking rides". 

The goal isn't to push production but to figure out what I'm actually doing and why and how.

I've had nearly two years off to think about what I *really* want to do in blockchain.
Toni Lane Casserly, pbuh, It will always be too soon, asked if I were an Ethereum developer when I joined

At that moment (I'm behind) I determined that yes, I am an Ethereum developer. 

And that's why I'm here.
